WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:50.484 --> 00:00:51.652
[country music]

00:00:54.826 --> 00:00:55.779
Good morning, guys.

00:00:55.846 --> 00:00:59.132
Today we have
quite an interesting road trip ahead of us.

00:00:59.199 --> 00:01:02.049
We're going through the Arkansas Delta.

00:01:02.484 --> 00:01:05.650
One of the poorest parts of the country.

00:01:06.069 --> 00:01:07.963
It's seen a huge population decline

00:01:08.422 --> 00:01:10.937
and an increase in crime.

00:01:11.004 --> 00:01:14.691
A lot of agriculture is still happening
but just less people working.

00:01:14.758 --> 00:01:16.423
More machines, less people.

00:01:18.756 --> 00:01:21.473
One side of the street
falling apart in Marianna.

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:23.060
One rising.

00:01:23.917 --> 00:01:25.469
Oh, look at that beauty.

00:01:26.353 --> 00:01:28.300
Marianna has got some gems.

00:01:28.773 --> 00:01:29.739
Huh.

00:01:29.806 --> 00:01:33.484
Okay. This is a pretty
dangerous place statistically.

00:01:33.961 --> 00:01:37.950
But coming in, I'm actually
quite surprised by what I'm seeing.

00:01:39.313 --> 00:01:41.197
We have a nice square here.

00:01:41.264 --> 00:01:43.504
Get out and walk around.
Talk to some people.

00:01:50.191 --> 00:01:52.445
-How you doing, sir?
-Good. How you doing?

00:01:52.512 --> 00:01:54.264
-You live here in Marianna?
-Yeah.

00:01:54.331 --> 00:01:55.353
How's it going?

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.984
-I'm good. I'm Justin.
-Peter.

00:01:58.051 --> 00:01:59.009
You're from here?

00:01:59.076 --> 00:01:59.959
-Yeah.
-Okay.

00:02:00.026 --> 00:02:01.343
Born and raised.

00:02:01.410 --> 00:02:02.939
-How are things these days?

00:02:03.463 --> 00:02:05.122
It's okay. It's peaceful.

00:02:05.189 --> 00:02:07.193
Good to hear. Is this your shop?

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:09.516
No, no. My godmama operates that shop.

00:02:09.583 --> 00:02:10.466
-Your godmama?

00:02:10.540 --> 00:02:14.128
-It's not really a lot to do,
but you got to make stuff to do.

00:02:14.915 --> 00:02:16.482
-I do farming.
-Oh, that's cool.

00:02:16.549 --> 00:02:18.608
So, I love it. It's very rewarding.

00:02:19.101 --> 00:02:20.757
-Farming is very rewarding?
-Yeah.

00:02:20.824 --> 00:02:23.118
And I volunteer at a food pantry, yeah.

00:02:24.252 --> 00:02:25.817
I'm gonna walk around, sir.

00:02:25.884 --> 00:02:28.355
-Nice to meet you.
-You too. Appreciate it.

00:02:28.982 --> 00:02:31.194
You can see wealth from the past

00:02:32.078 --> 00:02:34.607
in those houses
when we were coming into town.

00:02:34.674 --> 00:02:36.370
In buildings like this.

00:02:36.437 --> 00:02:37.908
This is cotton territory.

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.739
And the money flowed in here.

00:02:40.806 --> 00:02:43.938
There's a port here,
the Mississippi right over there.

00:02:44.005 --> 00:02:45.641
The port was thriving.

00:02:45.708 --> 00:02:47.238
Marianna had its heyday.

00:02:47.305 --> 00:02:49.616
And I gotta say
it looks better than I thought.

00:02:49.683 --> 00:02:51.504
Because on paper it went from

00:02:51.571 --> 00:02:54.491
roughly 6,200 people back in 1980

00:02:54.558 --> 00:02:57.887
to 3,200 right now.

00:02:57.954 --> 00:02:59.233
And crime…

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:02.115
Two homicides last year,
two homicides the year before.

00:03:02.182 --> 00:03:06.362
When you have 3,200 people,
that puts the percentages up big time.

00:03:06.853 --> 00:03:09.209
Poverty levels here are pretty high.

00:03:09.635 --> 00:03:11.503
One of the highest in the country.

00:03:11.570 --> 00:03:14.723
So, hey, good job here in Marianna
keeping the downtown nice

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:17.147
'cause you wouldn't know
just by coming in here.

00:03:17.214 --> 00:03:21.597
But it's roughly 56%
fall below the poverty line.

00:03:23.603 --> 00:03:27.143
"In loving memory of
the Lee County's Confederate soldiers."

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:29.034
That is Robert E. Lee up there.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:31.643
"No braver bled For a brighter land.

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:34.210
No brighter land had a cause so grand."

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:37.899
That will fire up the comments for sure.

00:03:37.972 --> 00:03:39.981
[woman mumbling angrily]

00:03:40.048 --> 00:03:40.931
-What's that?

00:03:41.021 --> 00:03:43.173
I got a freaking piece of paper
for a charge

00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:45.610
that they did not give me
when they arrested me.

00:03:45.677 --> 00:03:49.374
Then on top of that, I done filed
three different f*cking incident reports

00:03:49.441 --> 00:03:52.076
about my car that Preston Lane stole.

00:03:52.143 --> 00:03:53.906
And they had no record of it.

00:03:53.973 --> 00:03:56.629
-I'm fixin' to sue the…
-What happened to the car?

00:03:56.696 --> 00:03:58.972
He took it to the salvage yard.
He stole it.

00:03:59.039 --> 00:04:00.512
Him and two crackheads.

00:04:00.579 --> 00:04:02.783
They pulled it off my friend's property.

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:04.403
-Do you want this on a video?

00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:07.549
Man, like I'm just at the point
where I'm so sick of Marianna.

00:04:07.616 --> 00:04:09.566
They are useless. I grew up in Atlanta.

00:04:09.633 --> 00:04:14.023
Bro, the stuff people get away with
down here is really like unheard of.

00:04:14.090 --> 00:04:16.686
-What's it like right now?
-Bro, it's terrible.

00:04:16.753 --> 00:04:18.766
I freaking always hated Marianna.

00:04:18.833 --> 00:04:22.103
And ever since I've been an adult,
I really hate Marianna.

00:04:22.170 --> 00:04:25.283
I've gotten three different tickets
in this stupid a** town

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:29.963
for something that you charged me with
when you put me in handcuffs…

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:32.435
-So you're totally innocent? You didn't…

00:04:32.502 --> 00:04:33.564
I didn't do anything!

00:04:33.631 --> 00:04:36.877
I called them because
somebody put me out the house.

00:04:36.944 --> 00:04:39.593
I was bleeding,
had freaking handcuffs on my arm.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:42.833
I have a problem with my wrist,
they had to do freaking x-rays.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:46.120
And they said that
I was being like unreasonable.

00:04:46.887 --> 00:04:49.426
I stay in Montana.
I came back down here.

00:04:49.493 --> 00:04:51.809
-I just lost my brother yesterday.
-I'm sorry.

00:04:51.876 --> 00:04:55.096
I'm just at the point where
I'm just so over Arkansas as a whole.

00:04:55.163 --> 00:04:56.983
I only came to file my divorce.

00:04:57.393 --> 00:05:01.042
Freaking I lost my brother in the mix.
He just died like, bro, yesterday.

00:05:01.109 --> 00:05:03.979
And then on top of that,
I got arrested for some bullshit.

00:05:04.046 --> 00:05:06.463
I came down here
to make sure my name was clear.

00:05:06.530 --> 00:05:09.109
I just want to drop my marital status.
That was it.

00:05:09.176 --> 00:05:10.478
I wanted to be an officer.

00:05:10.545 --> 00:05:13.318
And watching them here,
it puts a bad name

00:05:13.385 --> 00:05:15.874
on any type of freaking law enforcement.

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:18.834
Marianna, they need to shut down
the police station

00:05:18.901 --> 00:05:20.842
and just give it to the sheriffs.

00:05:22.111 --> 00:05:27.096
In situations like that, when you're not
privy to all the information.

00:05:27.163 --> 00:05:29.488
Well, I have no idea what happened.

00:05:29.848 --> 00:05:33.065
So, just showing you
what I'm running into, you guys.

00:05:33.132 --> 00:05:36.476
See some of these
old buildings have come down.

00:05:36.543 --> 00:05:38.223
And then we have this place.

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:39.441
A lot of flags.

00:05:43.593 --> 00:05:45.233
You were born and raised in Marianna?

00:05:45.775 --> 00:05:49.215
Went to college
and got a degree and moved back home.

00:05:49.282 --> 00:05:50.982
That's cool. So this is your shop?

00:05:51.049 --> 00:05:53.163
Getting ready for all the summer holidays.

00:05:53.230 --> 00:05:56.880
I have all sorts of baby gifts,
patriotic decor,

00:05:56.947 --> 00:06:00.059
and just odd and end things you might need.

00:06:00.126 --> 00:06:03.797
-Any small business is tough.
Is this hard to make it fly in this town?

00:06:03.864 --> 00:06:05.087
It has its challenges.

00:06:05.154 --> 00:06:06.486
I just opened in November.

00:06:06.553 --> 00:06:08.653
-I taught school for 14 years.
-Okay.

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:09.603
I just opened.

00:06:10.166 --> 00:06:12.902
-You're another teacher that's left.
-Mm-hmm.

00:06:12.969 --> 00:06:14.545
I meet you guys all the time.

00:06:14.612 --> 00:06:16.200
I'm sure you do. In droves.

00:06:16.881 --> 00:06:19.247
-In droves.
That's the story across the country.

00:06:19.314 --> 00:06:22.839
-And I hate to say it, but it is.
-It's not just here. It's everywhere.

00:06:22.912 --> 00:06:26.219
A lot of young teachers
getting into small businesses like this.

00:06:26.286 --> 00:06:31.061
I do keep my teaching license and keep
the hours, keep my license current.

00:06:31.128 --> 00:06:32.037
-Okay.

00:06:32.104 --> 00:06:34.265
Hopefully I don't ever
have to use it again.

00:06:34.332 --> 00:06:35.948
-Really? Did you teach locally?

00:06:36.023 --> 00:06:37.773
Within like 30 minutes of here.

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:39.458
I never taught here in Marianna.

00:06:39.525 --> 00:06:42.085
-It's just become
more challenging over the years?

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:45.460
And I have my master's actually.
I wasn't in the classroom.

00:06:45.527 --> 00:06:47.033
I had gifted and talented.

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:49.533
So kids… filtered in and out all day.

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:51.160
And it's still…

00:06:51.782 --> 00:06:55.866
Still not the same today as it was
when I started 14 years ago.

00:06:56.276 --> 00:06:58.888
-It's changed that much in 14 years?
-Yeah.

00:06:59.976 --> 00:07:01.599
My great uncle, who's 91,

00:07:01.666 --> 00:07:05.750
bought my great aunt's
engagement ring here 70 years ago.

00:07:06.124 --> 00:07:08.987
-Maybe a little more than that.
-So it was a jewelry shop.

00:07:09.054 --> 00:07:11.412
And then it closed
and it was empty for a while.

00:07:11.479 --> 00:07:14.655
And it had started falling in
because of that building.

00:07:14.722 --> 00:07:18.268
And the county trust got a grant

00:07:18.335 --> 00:07:22.639
and they redid this building
and I was able to just walk in.

00:07:22.706 --> 00:07:23.589
-That's cool.

00:07:23.656 --> 00:07:27.647
And it's on the National Register
of Historic Places. That's so awesome.

00:07:27.714 --> 00:07:30.483
It's a good little town to live in.
I love it.

00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:33.282
We have a really good chief of police now.

00:07:33.349 --> 00:07:34.232
-Okay.

00:07:34.299 --> 00:07:36.126
And he runs a tight ship.

00:07:36.193 --> 00:07:39.296
So things have been
really good since he got here.

00:07:39.363 --> 00:07:41.030
So… When did he get here?

00:07:41.097 --> 00:07:44.214
I want to say within
the last six months to a year maybe.

00:07:44.281 --> 00:07:48.187
And then he and the sheriff,
the county sheriff, work closely together

00:07:48.254 --> 00:07:51.483
and they both keep things
under control pretty well. So…

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:53.363
-All right. Name of your business?

00:07:53.430 --> 00:07:55.570
It's Toodles Flowers &amp; Gifts.

00:07:55.637 --> 00:07:57.724
-Toodles Flowers &amp; Gifts.
-Yes, sir.

00:07:57.791 --> 00:07:59.789
-Ma'am. Thank you.
-You're welcome.

00:07:59.863 --> 00:08:00.746
-Take care.

00:08:01.814 --> 00:08:04.199
All right, guys.
Just showing you what I see.

00:08:04.266 --> 00:08:06.544
I'm gonna give you the good, the bad,

00:08:07.511 --> 00:08:09.040
and everything in between.

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:13.206
Never try to sugarcoat.
Never try to put a place under the bus.

00:08:13.273 --> 00:08:14.309
And look,

00:08:14.376 --> 00:08:16.178
I'm here for a short period of time.

00:08:16.244 --> 00:08:18.793
I'm coming in for a couple hours at most.

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:20.498
No expert on this town,

00:08:21.185 --> 00:08:24.563
but can take a little temperature
with the camera

00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:26.218
through the people we meet.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:28.749
And you guys can take it from there.

00:08:28.816 --> 00:08:32.478
This is interesting travel for me at least,
I think for a lot of you.

00:08:32.873 --> 00:08:36.447
If you're in Arkansas
and you want to cruise through the Delta,

00:08:36.897 --> 00:08:37.838
these towns are,

00:08:38.792 --> 00:08:40.503
they create a feel… Ugh!

00:08:41.349 --> 00:08:43.341
Like falling in a pothole…

00:08:43.408 --> 00:08:44.526
They create a feel.

00:08:45.269 --> 00:08:47.889
And most of the people usually

00:08:48.777 --> 00:08:49.718
are pretty cool.

00:08:49.785 --> 00:08:50.668
Look at this.

00:08:52.699 --> 00:08:54.758
I've never seen a hearse like that.

00:09:06.279 --> 00:09:09.025
Okay, sir.
So what are you doing here in Marianna?

00:09:09.092 --> 00:09:10.623
I'm a mental health therapist.

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:13.665
I work with children ages 5 to 18.

00:09:13.732 --> 00:09:14.727
-How's it going?

00:09:14.794 --> 00:09:16.843
That's a two-fold question.

00:09:16.910 --> 00:09:18.746
I love mental health.

00:09:18.813 --> 00:09:21.419
I love bringing awareness to mental health.

00:09:21.486 --> 00:09:24.938
We need so much more awareness.

00:09:25.005 --> 00:09:25.914
-Okay.

00:09:25.981 --> 00:09:27.970
Especially with our children,

00:09:28.037 --> 00:09:32.929
and especially in rural communities
with the stereotypes of mental health.

00:09:32.996 --> 00:09:36.462
In that sense, I love what I do
because I love bringing awareness,

00:09:36.529 --> 00:09:40.663
but it also makes me sad
to see so much mental health.

00:09:40.730 --> 00:09:43.703
-What are the kids needing
right now from what you see?

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:45.266
It would go beyond the kids.

00:09:45.333 --> 00:09:47.933
I would say we would have
to start with the parents.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.151
Parenting classes,
courses, skills, resources,

00:09:52.218 --> 00:09:56.675
especially in our
underdeveloped rural counties.

00:09:57.106 --> 00:09:58.667
They definitely need resources.

00:09:58.734 --> 00:10:01.317
Many of our children have not been exposed

00:10:01.384 --> 00:10:05.205
to the culture of things
that's right there within our own state.

00:10:05.272 --> 00:10:08.777
-I just met a former teacher,
and I hate to say it.

00:10:08.844 --> 00:10:11.933
I hear that story
all the time all over the country.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.700
Younger, former teachers.

00:10:13.767 --> 00:10:15.189
-Do you see that?
-I do.

00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:17.827
And they're just burning out or what?

00:10:17.894 --> 00:10:19.040
-Yes.
-Okay.

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:21.036
What do you do?

00:10:21.103 --> 00:10:23.963
How do you fix something
that's bigger than you?

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:27.564
-You're feeling ineffective.
-Right.

00:10:28.504 --> 00:10:30.586
So it's a collaboration between

00:10:31.333 --> 00:10:33.735
home life obviously and school life.

00:10:33.802 --> 00:10:34.756
And school life.

00:10:34.823 --> 00:10:37.123
-Not one can do it all.
-Not one can do it all.

00:10:37.190 --> 00:10:38.606
-They need each other.
-Yeah.

00:10:38.673 --> 00:10:41.991
So if the teachers
have students where the home life

00:10:42.058 --> 00:10:45.313
isn't so good and then
a lot of weight comes on them

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:46.384
and vice versa.

00:10:46.451 --> 00:10:50.802
And you know, we see it in Hollywood
with movies where they do things like,

00:10:51.565 --> 00:10:54.218
where children have basketball, taekwondo.

00:10:54.285 --> 00:10:57.382
You know, we see it,
but we don't have those.

00:10:57.885 --> 00:11:00.335
You know, we have a basketball team
at the school,

00:11:00.402 --> 00:11:02.402
but it's got what, 12, 15 players?

00:11:02.916 --> 00:11:04.323
Where the rest of them go?

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:05.526
Or what if I'm not…

00:11:05.593 --> 00:11:09.173
How do you get them motivated
'cause it's a personal decision.

00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:10.181
Kids gotta want…

00:11:10.248 --> 00:11:14.474
They need the leadership,
but they have to want to do it, right?

00:11:14.541 --> 00:11:17.393
And they have to know that it exists.

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:19.483
For example, if I'm a teenage boy,

00:11:19.875 --> 00:11:21.640
but I'm not good at sports,

00:11:22.175 --> 00:11:23.401
what do I do?

00:11:23.468 --> 00:11:25.437
I don't know anything about poetry.

00:11:25.504 --> 00:11:27.156
I've never been exposed to it.

00:11:27.223 --> 00:11:30.152
-I don't know anything about skateboarding.
-Yeah, okay.

00:11:30.226 --> 00:11:32.870
I've never surfed before.

00:11:33.213 --> 00:11:36.116
You know, so a lot of times
they're not exposed.

00:11:36.183 --> 00:11:38.550
-Bad news,
that might not be happening out here.

00:11:38.617 --> 00:11:41.090
-I'm sure we're not gonna surf.
-The surfing part.

00:11:41.157 --> 00:11:42.981
-Surfing the delta.
-Yeah, yeah.

00:11:43.391 --> 00:11:45.354
You know, but I think a lot of times

00:11:45.421 --> 00:11:49.378
they would know that they have these
hidden talents if they could be exposed.

00:11:49.445 --> 00:11:51.596
-There's a lot of talent out here.
-It is.

00:11:51.663 --> 00:11:55.453
I was just in Little Rock,
south of the line in the so-called hood.

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:56.776
A lot of talent in there.

00:11:56.843 --> 00:11:59.803
And they just need like that
connection to the thing.

00:12:00.164 --> 00:12:01.047
Exactly.

00:12:01.114 --> 00:12:03.679
-It's the mindset too,
knowing that it's possible.

00:12:03.746 --> 00:12:07.553
And there's several components,
they need someone that believe in them.

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:10.230
Johnny's parent may not know how.

00:12:10.706 --> 00:12:15.316
Not that she's a bad parent, but she just
may not know how to be a support system.

00:12:15.383 --> 00:12:19.030
So sometimes mentoring
is good for both the kid and the parent.

00:12:19.546 --> 00:12:21.666
-It's a deep problem.
-It's a deep problem.

00:12:21.733 --> 00:12:24.161
But people like you
I really respect for helping.

00:12:24.228 --> 00:12:26.346
So, and I got to say on a side note,

00:12:26.985 --> 00:12:29.632
people are super friendly here.
Everyone's waving.

00:12:29.699 --> 00:12:31.074
You know, a lot of smiles.

00:12:31.141 --> 00:12:33.220
Southern hospitality is a real thing.

00:12:33.287 --> 00:12:35.626
-Real thing.
-It's a real thing. [chuckles]

00:12:36.073 --> 00:12:39.512
The Lord said your children
should be obedient to their parents

00:12:39.579 --> 00:12:40.749
and show them respect.

00:12:40.816 --> 00:12:43.549
But you also should
show your children respect.

00:12:43.616 --> 00:12:45.641
You should invest in your children.

00:12:45.708 --> 00:12:47.889
You should teach them
and show them the way.

00:12:47.956 --> 00:12:50.663
Let them know all about the Savior,
the Lord thy God.

00:12:50.730 --> 00:12:52.259
And show them the way.

00:12:52.326 --> 00:12:54.440
Because without God, you can't make it.

00:12:54.507 --> 00:12:56.891
-You get valet service here?

00:12:56.958 --> 00:12:58.017
You also need the…

00:12:58.941 --> 00:13:00.848
The world teaching.

00:13:00.915 --> 00:13:03.091
Also, we need the spiritual teaching.

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:05.563
-So you think we need more of that?

00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:06.630
-Yes, I do.
-Okay.

00:13:06.697 --> 00:13:08.463
Because let me tell you something.

00:13:08.530 --> 00:13:11.286
There's a lot of these children
walking around here,

00:13:11.353 --> 00:13:14.316
got mothers, and don't even know
nothing about the Savior.

00:13:14.383 --> 00:13:15.292
You understand me?

00:13:15.359 --> 00:13:19.459
And they just doing what they see they
parents doing because they have no teacher.

00:13:19.526 --> 00:13:22.538
Nobody to tell them.
Show them right from wrong.

00:13:22.605 --> 00:13:25.857
These young people out here,
they walk and they go here and there.

00:13:25.924 --> 00:13:29.685
They don't have nobody
to tell them that they're loved.

00:13:29.752 --> 00:13:32.646
They don't have nobody
to tell them that you can make it.

00:13:32.713 --> 00:13:35.034
They don't have nobody
to teach them, you know,

00:13:35.101 --> 00:13:37.354
to show them the way
like my mother taught me.

00:13:37.421 --> 00:13:40.353
Now see my father
weren't in my life until I were 14.

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:44.674
But my mother taught me what was wrong,
what was right, how to work.

00:13:44.741 --> 00:13:47.266
I started working
at five years old in the field.

00:13:47.333 --> 00:13:49.509
I might not have a college education,

00:13:50.074 --> 00:13:53.124
but I always worked and made my own money.

00:13:53.191 --> 00:13:56.119
My mama said your own money
is better than anybody's money.

00:13:56.186 --> 00:13:58.971
But my grandkids and my children too.

00:13:59.038 --> 00:14:02.552
And I have grandchildren that graduate
college is going to be a lawyer,

00:14:02.618 --> 00:14:04.996
going to be an accountant,
going to be doctors.

00:14:05.063 --> 00:14:08.948
I got all that going on
on my great-grandchildren's side.

00:14:09.015 --> 00:14:11.551
I don't mind working,
making me a dollar or two.

00:14:11.618 --> 00:14:14.394
I don't have to go out there
and beg nobody for nothing.

00:14:14.461 --> 00:14:17.884
You hear what I'm saying?!
I'm taking care of my great-grandchildren!

00:14:17.951 --> 00:14:20.074
Glory to God! Hallelujah!

00:14:20.141 --> 00:14:21.149
Thank you, Lord.

00:14:21.216 --> 00:14:23.804
-You fired me up.
-God is good! You hear me?!

00:14:24.460 --> 00:14:26.092
You got to teach these children!

00:14:26.159 --> 00:14:28.020
Teach them about the law of the land.

00:14:28.087 --> 00:14:31.051
You got to teach them about God.
You got to discipline them.

00:14:31.118 --> 00:14:33.347
-You hear what I'm saying?
-Loud and clear.

00:14:33.414 --> 00:14:37.529
You got to discipline them. You ain't
got to beat them and disrespect them.

00:14:37.596 --> 00:14:39.814
But just talk to them nice
and let them know.

00:14:39.881 --> 00:14:42.343
Hey, I'm the boss, you do what I say to do.

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:43.881
And how I said do.

00:14:43.948 --> 00:14:45.316
See what I'm saying?

00:14:45.383 --> 00:14:47.442
I've never been in debt in my life.

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:49.257
Never been there.

00:14:49.860 --> 00:14:51.917
She just lost her brother. He got killed.

00:14:51.984 --> 00:14:53.513
Oh yeah, she just told me.

00:14:54.781 --> 00:14:56.720
-That's brutal.
-Amen baby.

00:14:57.312 --> 00:14:59.645
-So these children get in deep…
-Excuse me.

00:14:59.712 --> 00:15:04.398
…relationships and stuff
and they don't know how to get out of it.

00:15:04.465 --> 00:15:05.348
-What's that?

00:15:05.415 --> 00:15:08.998
They get in these bad relationships
and they don't know how to get out.

00:15:09.065 --> 00:15:11.207
Sometimes they kill each other.

00:15:12.575 --> 00:15:16.508
Because they ain't been taught nothing.
They ain't been teaching nothing.

00:15:17.001 --> 00:15:21.060
-It all comes from the parenting.
-No love, no counseling, no nothing.

00:15:26.913 --> 00:15:29.715
I wonder what this was.
You can see the columns here.

00:15:29.782 --> 00:15:31.235
Spaced out in the front.

00:15:31.302 --> 00:15:33.860
I'm sure a beautiful building.

00:15:33.927 --> 00:15:35.925
And you can see the floor here.

00:15:35.992 --> 00:15:38.671
That nice tile floor.

00:15:38.738 --> 00:15:40.424
Not long ago.

00:15:40.491 --> 00:15:42.556
Probably a bank I'm guessing.

00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:45.119
People were walking in here.

00:15:45.186 --> 00:15:47.608
The money was coming in.
The money was going out.

00:15:47.675 --> 00:15:50.049
Or any local here tell us what this was.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:52.572
Ah, that's too bad.

00:15:52.639 --> 00:15:56.970
This is on the National Register
of Historic Places also.

00:15:58.973 --> 00:16:00.113
Huh. What is that?

00:16:00.180 --> 00:16:02.239
The plants growing from the inside?

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:05.585
Never seen anything like that.

00:16:06.115 --> 00:16:10.329
Where the building is getting eaten out
by nature from the inside.

00:16:11.277 --> 00:16:12.403
That is so wild.

00:16:13.956 --> 00:16:16.949
Marianna, you're gonna see this though,
lines down.

00:16:17.687 --> 00:16:20.817
Once you get off that main square
where we were,

00:16:21.752 --> 00:16:23.399
it starts turning into this.

00:16:33.159 --> 00:16:34.428
This is interesting.

00:16:34.495 --> 00:16:37.881
There are actually
some really cute homes here.

00:16:38.368 --> 00:16:42.316
I mean, you're getting this
for nothing in these parts.

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:46.120
This is just like literally
a quarter mile from

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:48.247
the downtown area.

00:16:48.314 --> 00:16:51.750
I'm guessing these are
the business people

00:16:51.817 --> 00:16:56.423
in and around Marianna
that have agricultural businesses.

00:16:56.490 --> 00:16:57.856
I'm guessing that.

00:16:57.923 --> 00:16:58.883
Don't know.

00:16:59.276 --> 00:17:01.832
And it goes to this
pretty much immediately.

00:17:10.576 --> 00:17:13.261
Alright guys, right here,
the end of last year,

00:17:13.328 --> 00:17:16.137
there was a homicide
right at this intersection.

00:17:16.503 --> 00:17:17.738
Chestnut and Alabama.

00:17:18.236 --> 00:17:21.204
A 20 year old was shot and killed.

00:17:21.802 --> 00:17:24.155
And unfortunately, you hear a lot of that

00:17:24.911 --> 00:17:29.215
in some of these rougher parts
of Arkansas and across the Deep South.

00:17:30.602 --> 00:17:31.720
Across the country.

00:17:32.709 --> 00:17:34.786
You know, in the rougher neighborhoods

00:17:35.232 --> 00:17:38.710
where something like
someone got shot over 20 bucks.

00:17:38.777 --> 00:17:39.992
Something like that.

00:17:40.059 --> 00:17:43.462
Saw it in Pine Bluff,
a video I did a few weeks ago.

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:45.276
Like the woman said,

00:17:46.502 --> 00:17:48.087
sweeping earlier today.

00:17:48.975 --> 00:17:52.376
It all comes from the parents,
the community, the schooling.

00:17:52.856 --> 00:17:55.489
And if you don't have good parenting,

00:17:55.556 --> 00:17:59.411
rewards, positivity, and consequences,

00:17:59.478 --> 00:18:01.277
then things get out of line.

00:18:01.802 --> 00:18:03.203
And you get that.

00:18:03.636 --> 00:18:06.689
A 20 year old
who shouldn't have died, dying.

00:18:08.076 --> 00:18:10.508
Okay, so this town,
I think we've seen enough.

00:18:10.575 --> 00:18:13.100
Let's get off to the next town,

00:18:13.494 --> 00:18:15.215
Helena-West Helena.

00:18:15.660 --> 00:18:16.543
[country music]

00:18:29.256 --> 00:18:32.076
[Peter] These are
pretty amazing machines, huh?

00:18:32.144 --> 00:18:34.343
Yeah, technology's come a long way.

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:38.795
-So the Delta right now, the agriculture
is thriving for the most part, right?

00:18:38.862 --> 00:18:41.045
Like people making good livings out here?

00:18:41.112 --> 00:18:43.215
Well, it's been tough.

00:18:43.282 --> 00:18:45.164
This past year was really tough.

00:18:45.231 --> 00:18:47.937
Prices were not good.
It was just a tough year.

00:18:48.460 --> 00:18:51.093
This equipment, everything's so expensive.

00:18:51.160 --> 00:18:54.629
What's a tractor like that
costing out the door?

00:18:55.256 --> 00:18:59.189
It's probably close to $400,000,
if not more.

00:18:59.256 --> 00:19:00.790
-$400,000? Wow.

00:19:00.857 --> 00:19:02.210
Probably a little more.

00:19:02.810 --> 00:19:04.666
Commodity prices have stayed.

00:19:04.733 --> 00:19:08.715
They're at the same price they would
probably had in the 40s and 50s for cotton.

00:19:08.782 --> 00:19:11.332
Cotton this past year
was the 60 cent range.

00:19:11.399 --> 00:19:12.943
-60 cent a pound?
-Yes.

00:19:13.415 --> 00:19:16.338
So I see a lot of nice houses
here in the countryside.

00:19:16.405 --> 00:19:17.711
A lot of nice properties.

00:19:17.778 --> 00:19:20.161
So people are doing pretty well
out here, right?

00:19:20.228 --> 00:19:25.279
Well, there's been some that's been
fortunate enough to have some good years.

00:19:25.857 --> 00:19:27.102
It's a decent living.

00:19:27.169 --> 00:19:30.612
It's a lot of hard work,
a lot of worry, a lot of stress.

00:19:30.679 --> 00:19:33.135
-And stress with stuff
that's out of your control,

00:19:33.202 --> 00:19:35.210
like commodity prices and the weather.

00:19:35.277 --> 00:19:36.749
How much is your diesel here?

00:19:36.816 --> 00:19:39.642
Well farm fuel's probably
in the $4.00 range.

00:19:40.256 --> 00:19:43.528
Highway, road fuel's probably,
I hadn't looked, probably $5.00.

00:19:44.168 --> 00:19:48.109
-Anything you'd want to tell the country
from a farmer's perspective?

00:19:49.190 --> 00:19:52.668
I just don't think they realize
how important the agriculture is.

00:19:53.160 --> 00:19:54.296
It comes from a farm.

00:19:54.363 --> 00:19:56.363
It just don't show up at the grocery store.

00:19:56.430 --> 00:19:58.981
-What do you think of
the solar panels coming in?

00:19:59.048 --> 00:20:00.959
Driving in here from the highway,

00:20:01.026 --> 00:20:03.599
coming into these fields,
what do you think on that?

00:20:03.666 --> 00:20:07.342
I don't like it. If it was some land
that was pretty much useless,

00:20:07.409 --> 00:20:09.623
won't grow any crops or anything,

00:20:10.303 --> 00:20:14.009
I don't see a problem with it, but I hate
to see them put on good cropland.

00:20:14.076 --> 00:20:18.319
-You know, I do too. It just like,
at a visceral level, it feels off

00:20:18.386 --> 00:20:21.537
because this land
is where we get our food from.

00:20:21.604 --> 00:20:23.914
To cover it all with panels
would take forever.

00:20:23.981 --> 00:20:26.895
But if you're covering
some of that great land with panels…

00:20:26.962 --> 00:20:28.872
-Sort of an industrial material…
-Yeah.

00:20:28.939 --> 00:20:32.292
…on top that's toxic,
if it cracks or breaks,

00:20:32.808 --> 00:20:36.529
it doesn't make sense to… like,
you don't want to ruin that soil, right?

00:20:36.596 --> 00:20:37.479
Right.

00:20:37.546 --> 00:20:40.360
-Put it in industrial areas,
top of buildings.

00:20:40.427 --> 00:20:41.310
Right.

00:20:41.377 --> 00:20:43.393
-Out in the desert.
-Yes, yes.

00:20:43.460 --> 00:20:45.754
I just hate to see them go up,
but you know,

00:20:45.821 --> 00:20:48.696
I guess as a landowner,
it's hard to turn that money down.

00:20:48.763 --> 00:20:51.249
-Is it good?
-It's pretty good from what I hear.

00:20:51.316 --> 00:20:53.069
-They make a good offer?
-I think it is.

00:20:53.136 --> 00:20:55.129
I couldn't tell you exactly what it is.

00:20:55.196 --> 00:20:59.676
So if someone said we'd love to
put solar panels on your field,

00:20:59.743 --> 00:21:02.729
there's gonna be a price
for you eventually, right?

00:21:02.796 --> 00:21:05.256
If they say five mil, you're gonna do it?

00:21:05.323 --> 00:21:07.228
Well, every field that I work, I rent.

00:21:07.295 --> 00:21:09.936
I don't own one piece of property.
I rent everything.

00:21:10.003 --> 00:21:11.464
-Okay, but if you did own it?

00:21:11.531 --> 00:21:13.981
If I did own it,
I don't think I could do it. No.

00:21:14.048 --> 00:21:15.782
-Just out of principle?
-Yeah.

00:21:15.849 --> 00:21:19.147
I won't say I wouldn't do it,
but you know, it's hard to…

00:21:20.108 --> 00:21:23.192
You were put in that position,
you never know what the situation is.

00:21:23.259 --> 00:21:24.980
-All of a sudden something happens,

00:21:25.047 --> 00:21:28.677
unfortunately, you have health expenses,
some things happen in your life.

00:21:28.744 --> 00:21:30.554
Someone said, here's five mil,

00:21:30.621 --> 00:21:33.056
you don't have to work
on your field anymore.

00:21:33.123 --> 00:21:34.711
It's tough to say no, right?

00:21:34.778 --> 00:21:36.857
It would be tempting. It really would.

00:21:36.924 --> 00:21:38.453
But I sure hate to see it.

00:21:38.829 --> 00:21:41.115
-All right, sir.
Well, thank you for your work.

00:21:41.182 --> 00:21:43.233
-We couldn't live without you guys.
-Appreciate it.

00:21:43.300 --> 00:21:45.090
-Be careful.
-Thank you, sir.

